struggle over the nature of colonial governance. Cameron D. Jones reveals the changes that Spain's far-flung empire experienced from borderland Franciscan missions in Peru to the court of the Bourbon monarchy in Madrid, arguing that the Bourbon clerical reforms that broadly sought to bring the empire under greater crown control were shaped in turn by groups throughout the Americas, including Ocopa friars, the Amerindians and Africans in their missions, and bureaucrats in Lima and Madrid. Far from isolated local incidents, Jones argues that these conflicts were representative of the political struggles over clerical reform occurring throughout Spanish America on the eve of independence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFranciscansxMissionszPeruxHistoryy18th century. 0aIndians of South AmericaxMissionszPeruxHistoryy18th century. 4aApostolic Institute. 4aBourbon Reforms. 4aCatholic Church. 4aCatholic Evangelization of the Americas. 4aFranciscan missionaries. 4aJuan Santos Atahualpa. 4aPeruvian Amazon. 4aSanta Rosa de Ocopa. 4aSpanish Borderlands. 4aSpanish Colonialism. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503608382zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503608382423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503608382.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles